11. Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

> "The grid can be viewed as a graph where entering an unsafe cell costs one unit of health. A brute-force DFS explores every possible path, which is exponential. A better BFS treats each state as (row, col, remainingHealth), but it may revisit cells with different health values. The optimal solution uses Dijkstra's idea with a max heap. For each cell, we store the maximum remaining health seen so far. If we reach the same cell with less health, that state is discarded because it can never lead to a better solution. This gives a time complexity of O(mn log(mn)) and O(mn) space."




---

12. Key Takeaways

Treat the grid as a graph.

Health is the state, not path length.

More remaining health always dominates less remaining health.

Dijkstra with a max heap efficiently explores the best states first.

best[][] eliminates redundant work.



---

13. Common Mistakes

Forgetting to subtract the starting cell's cost.

Allowing health to become 0 (it must stay strictly positive).

Using normal BFS without tracking remaining health.

Revisiting a cell even when the new health is not better.

Forgetting the stale-state check (if hp < best[x][y]: continue).

Marking cells as permanently visited in the optimal solution.



